1. If the token is invalid, your code will always hit the `return;` line, after the subscribtion.

2. You return from inside the `subscribe` method, which is a void method. So nothing will happen, because there is nothing that will subscribe to the new request.

To fixe the problem you have to set up a propper async handling.

    if (!this.checkJwtTokenIsValid(jwtToken)) { //Invalid token, get new one
      const authTokenStream = this._authService.getAuthorizationToken$();

      return authTokenStream.pipe(
        take(1), 
        switchMap(newToken =&gt; {

        if(!this.checkJwtTokenIsValid(newToken)) //Still invalid
        {
          this._authService.signOut(&quot;jwtInvalid&quot;); //Don&#39;t log out, get new token
          return EMPTY;
        }

        req = this.addHeaders(req);

        return next.handle(req).pipe(
          catchError(error =&gt; {
            if (error instanceof HttpErrorResponse &amp;&amp; error.status === 401) {
              this._authService.signOut(&quot;unauthorized&quot;);
            }
            if (error instanceof HttpErrorResponse &amp;&amp; error.status === 403) {
              this._authService.signOut(&quot;expired&quot;);
            }
            return throwError(error);
          })
        );
      }))
    }

The switchMap operator is now subscribing to your tokenStream and the returning the new request observable. In this way the request pipe still has a request to subscribe on.
For more info about switchMap [here][1].


  [1]: https://www.learnrxjs.io/operators/transformation/switchmap.html

